===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|leren}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lǣran||to teach, instruct, indoctrinate}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*laizijaną||to teach}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*laizō||lore, teaching", literally, "track, trace}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*leyəs-||to track, furrow}}. Cognate with Scots {{term|lere|lang=sco}}, {{term|leir|lang=sco}}, Saterland Frisian {{term|leere|lang=stq}}, West Frisian {{term|leare|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|leren|lang=nl}}, German {{term|lehren|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|lära|lang=sv}}. See also {{l|en|lear}}, {{l|en|lore}}.

